Have you recruited talent for the company?
This way you will keep it from being "snatched" by your competitors.
The economy is still in a labor market that is mostly dominated by workers, and this is even more true when it comes to the most desirable workers – the talents.
Here are some tips to help you keep it in the workplace
.
Despite the increase in the past month, the unemployment rate in Israel continues to be one of the lowest in the world, and in the top ten of the OECD countries, with a rate of 3.5% (150,600 unemployed, according to the Central Bureau of Statistics).
In other words, the economy is still in a labor market that is mostly dominated by workers, and this is even more true when it comes to the most desirable workers – the talented ones.
When it comes to those professionals and managers who are centers of knowledge, experience, and proven ability, the trends in the labor market show that the competition for them, the talents as they are called by the employers, is still in full swing.
What this means for employers is that in the current state of the labor market, they don't have the luxury of resting on their laurels even a minute after recruiting a coveted talent, because as soon as he enters the company's gates, another company will already try to snatch him to it.
In other words, the competition for talent is so fierce that many will continue to receive a variety of tempting job offers even after being hired, with 30% of employees indeed leaving only about a month after receiving the job and starting work.
This is why wise employers will immediately move from the stage of recruiting talent to the stage of retaining it, with the path beginning first and foremost with preparation in advance and taking creativity already in the process of hiring him.
An efficient, structured and thoughtful onboarding process will make the talent excited about their new workplace from day one and even look forward to the future.
Here are some tips on how to prepare and manage the right onboarding process that will help retain the new talent:
It's Not a Secret - Sharing and Organizational Readiness |
Share with the parties who will work with him on his recruitment, explain to them why he is essential and important to the company and the position, and how you see his contribution.
A new employee who arrives at a place where he is expected and understands his value will feel welcome and will strive to prove the expectations that are planted in him.
Knowledge is Power - Setting Expectations |
On the first day, they had a conversation with the talent to coordinate expectations.
Get to know his professional background and check where he sees himself in the future, so that you can show him the diverse and unique tools that you and your workplace can provide him to get there.
We Are All People – Personal Acquaintance |
During the absorption days, try to get to know the talent beyond his professional qualities and be interested in his hobbies and interests.
A new employee who shows interest in him and allows him to realize and express himself beyond the boundaries of his job will appreciate this and will want to maintain it.
Curiosity Advances |
Already at the absorption stage, you can create an attractiveness that will make the talent want to integrate quickly.
Do this not necessarily through a discourse of bonuses and benefits, but by exposing him to an exciting field or interesting technology, as such stimuli for creativity lead to curiosity and increased interest in the workplace.
Also, encourage the talent to voice his thoughts and opinions on the various projects in the company and make it clear to him that they are important to the organization.
The writer is the CEO of Manpower Israel – Israel's largest placement and manpower company
Pocket electrification: The cost of not closing the coal plants in June is NIS 1 billion
Report by the Knesset Research and Information Center: Failure to Close the Coal-fired Plants on the June 2022 Date Estimated at NIS 1 Billion
• IEC: "The policy on the use of fuels is dictated first and foremost by the Ministry of Energy"
.
The economic cost of not closing the coal plants on the June 2022 date is estimated at about NIS 1 billion for 2022, according to a report by the Knesset Research and Information Center.
According to the report, this cost is reflected in the consumer electricity tariff, which is expected to rise in the coming months due to the increase in the price of coal.
In addition, in 2023, an additional amount of coal use is expected to be about 900,000 tons, so that this will be reflected in an additional cost to the electricity sector due to the non-closure of the coal plants, assuming that the price of natural gas will remain significantly lower than the price of coal.
The report states that the significance of a reduction of about NIS 1 billion in the electricity tariff in 2022 was a reduction of about 4% in the tariff for electricity consumption for the domestic consumer.
In other words, the economic cost of not closing the stations is about NIS 1 billion, and the total reduction that could have been made for the domestic consumer is about 4%.
It should be noted that as part of the reform in the electricity sector, it was decided, among other things, to establish a subsidiary of the Israel Electric Corporation, which will establish units powered by natural gas, which are intended to replace the 1-4 coal-fired units at the Orot Rabin site.
Following this decision, a government decision was made in July 2018, stating that the activity of the 1-4 coal production units at the Orot Rabin power plant must be stopped.
The decision set timetables, so that the construction of the first natural gas unit will begin in January 2020 and its operation will begin in June 2022, and accordingly, the 1-4 coal production units will also cease operating on that date.
The IEC said in response: "The policy on the use of fuels is dictated first and foremost by the Ministry of Energy.
In accordance with the Ministry's decisions, a policy has been implemented in Israel for several years to reduce the use of coal to the minimum possible, even when the price of coal is lower than the price of gas."
Paying the price: Everything you need to know ahead of the interest rate hike
Continuous Decrees: Next week the interest rate on the shekel is expected to rise by half a percentage point •
How much will the mortgage payment cost?
And what is recommended to do? •
All Answers
The worsening inflation in Israel, which has already reached a rate of more than 4 percent over the past year, will force the Bank of Israel to raise the interest rate on the shekel as early as next week.
Analysts' estimates speak of an increase rate of between 0.25 percent and 0.5 percent.
If the interest rate does increase by half a percent, it will already be 1.25 percent, the highest level in nine years.
This is after the interest rate in the economy was close to zero for years.
The sharp increase in the interest rate increases mortgage repayments by hundreds of shekels and drastically burdens households.
With the help of Shai Tzror, a mortgage expert, we examined how much more we will pay and what is recommended to do right now.
If the interest rate rises by half a percent, how much will the monthly payment on the mortgage be?
For a mortgage of NIS 1.2 million, which consists of a 40% prime interest track, the monthly repayment will increase by NIS 125.
How much has the average mortgage become more expensive since the beginning of the year?
Since the beginning of the year, this is a significantly sharper increase.
This is because interest rates in the other tracks that make up a mortgage (and not only in the prime track) also increased – in the index-linked track and in the fixed-rate track.
If the interest rate does increase by half a percent, the increase will amount, according to Tzror's estimate, to about 620 shekels in a mortgage of about 1.2 million shekels.
The prime track (40% in this track) will complete the increase in the price of about NIS 280, assuming that there will be an increase of another 0.5% next month.
The CPI-linked variable interest rate track (26.7% in this track) will complement the increase in the price of about NIS 120.
The fixed-interest track – not index-linked (33.3% in this track) will increase by NIS 220.
So what is recommended to do today?
For those who have a mortgage that is mostly linked to the index, Tzror recommends considering refinancing to non-indexed tracks.
For mortgage holders for whom the monthly repayment has increased significantly and it is difficult for them to meet the repayments - he recommends that they consider refinancing a mortgage and redeploy it for a longer period.
This is in order to reduce payments despite the increase in interest rates, since it is always better to meet the repayments and not be in default.
Regarding new mortgage borrowers - he highly recommends getting to know the different tracks and adapting the mortgage to their financial capabilities.
Similarly, in the future, when interest rates fall, they will be able to refinance a mortgage with minimal early repayment fees.
As for buyers of apartments from a contractor - Tzror recommends making payments to the contractor early and taking out a mortgage now.
It should be taken into account that the "construction input index" significantly increases the price of the property even after the purchase contract has been signed.
The price index of residential construction inputs increased by 6.6 percent in the past year.
Against the background of the increase in the cost of this index, the Banking Supervision Department announced yesterday that it is considering the creation of a mechanism that will enable the inclusion of linkages within mortgages, but a final decision on the matter has not yet been made.
The price of gasoline is becoming more expensive - and Israelis will have to pay more than 8 shekels per liter in July
The Ministry of Energy announced that the new price per liter of 95-octane gasoline will be NIS 8.08 •
At the same time, the reduction of half NIS per liter in the tax on diesel will be extended until the end of 2022
A decade high: The price of gasoline will jump by 36 agorot per liter - and will stand at more than 8 shekels per liter as of July 1.
The new price per liter of 95-octane gasoline will be 8.08, and those who wish to enjoy full service will be required to pay an additional 21 agorot per liter.
At the same time, the reduction of half a shekel per liter in the diesel tax will be extended until the end of 2022, according to the Tax Authority.
As noted, the price increase stems from the continued rise in oil prices, against the background of the war between Russia and Ukraine and the rise in the dollar rate.
If it weren't for the half-shekel discount that the government has subsidized since April, the price of gasoline would have surpassed an all-time high of 8.25 shekels per liter.
The discount expires at the end of July, and the Tax Authority and the Ministry of Finance are currently promoting the publication for public comments of an order extending the reduction in the tax on gasoline, which stands at half a shekel per liter, until August 9.
In addition, as of August 10, an additional reduction of another half shekel will be set, so that only from that date will the price of a liter of gasoline be reduced by one shekel, until November 15, 2022.
This was reported by the Tax Authority.
"We have reached a situation where I don't remember five months in a row of surplus state revenues.
We started a few months ago with the issue of reducing the tax on diesel.
We have been working for a week on an extension of the excise, gasoline and diesel tax for another four months – instead of half a shekel per shekel.
It's good for industry and the citizen.
If we lower it, it will affect inflation, reduce production, and ease the cost of living.
As finance minister, despite the election campaign, I intend to focus first and foremost on this," Liberman said at the Israel Democracy Institute's Hurwitz Conference on Economics and Society.
Currently, more than half of the price of fuel is taxed by the government (excise duty and VAT) – and this is a high tax rate compared to most developed countries.
The price of fuel has a dramatic impact on the cost of living in the economy – because it affects both household and business expenses, the prices of public transportation and flights, transportation costs, and more.
For the third time in a row: Ashdod - the friendliest city for business
Petah Tikva came in second place in the Ministry of Economy's Doing Business ranking •
Afterwards: Rehovot, Ashkelon and Rishon Lezion •
Minister Barbivai: "The coronavirus has emphasized the importance of local government in business development"
.
Ashdod is the most friendly city for small and medium-sized businesses.
This is the third year in a row, according to the Doing Business in Local Authorities Index of the Small and Medium Businesses Agency at the Ministry of Economy and Industry, which ranked the local authorities.
In second place is the city of Petah Tikva and in third place is Rehovot.
They are followed in order: Ashkelon, Rishon LeZion, Tel Aviv-Jaffa, Haifa, Ramat Gan, Holon, Be'er Sheva, Jerusalem, Bat Yam, Netanya and Bnei Brak.
The agency compiles the Local Authorities Index.
This is the fifth time and its purpose is to serve as a work tool for the local authority, as it allows each authority to compare its performance with other authorities in a variety of parameters, as well as to analyze its performance in the areas in which it is active.
The index is based on several parameters that are examined in each municipality, which examine the level of "friendliness" of the authority to businesses located in its area.
The index divides municipalities into three size groups according to the number of residents, since a local authority with up to 50,000 residents is not the same as a local authority with more than 150,000 residents.
Tel Aviv soared this year
The index is updated once a year and weighs four different rankings in each local authority: business satisfaction, accessibility to tenders, accessibility of information and municipal taxes.
The ranking shows that Ramat Gan dropped from second place to eighth place, Bat Yam dropped from fourth place to 12th place, and Netanya dropped from fifth place to 13th place.
A decrease in the ranking does not mean that the authority's service to businesses has deteriorated, and in many cases it is due to the fact that the service of other authorities to businesses has improved more and they have increased in the ranking, while the authority that declined in the ranking has improved its services to businesses less.
Among the top performers in the ranking are Petah Tikva, which rose from sixth place to second place, and Rehovot, which rose from 12th to third place.
Tel Aviv, which dropped from fourth place to 11th place in 2019, improved in 2021 and rose to sixth place.
"Business is a growth engine"
The ranking shows that Nof HaGalil leads in local authorities, which include between 50,000 and 150,000 residents.
It is followed by Kiryat Motzkin, Mateh Binyamin, Modi'in-Maccabim-Reut, Kfar Saba, Ra'anana, Nahariya, Karmiel, Afula and Hod Hasharon.
In 28th and last place is Tiberias.
"The index is intended to encourage local authorities to facilitate small and medium-sized businesses, starting from the date of opening the business and throughout its activity with the authorities," says Minister of Economy and Industry Orna Barbivai.
"Businesses are a significant growth engine for the Israeli economy and are responsible for about 50% of business output and about 60% of those employed in the economy.
The development of small businesses is in the public interest of all of us, but the local authority has a direct impact on the businesses in it.
The coronavirus has emphasized the importance of local government, and we have seen that authorities that have acted and encouraged the promotion of small businesses and found creative solutions for them, have become the first governmental interface for them."
Ran Kouti, Director of the Small and Medium Businesses Agency at the Ministry of Economy and Industry, adds: "Local authorities play a central and essential role in the ability of businesses in their field to thrive and flourish.
In the past two years, during which we have been dealing with the coronavirus crisis, the authorities have had a greater weight in helping businesses survive in their area and survive in general."
2021 by Mail: 20 Packages Per Household - and Weight Gain
46.6 million parcels arrived in Israel in 2021 - similar to 2020 •
The average weight per package is 435 grams - a 36% jump compared to 2020 •
The busiest month: December, when the average package weight was 524 grams.
In 2021, 46.6 million postal parcels arrived in Israel, an average of almost 20 parcels per household, according to Israel Postal data obtained by Israel Hayom.
The number of packages that arrived in 2021 is similar to 2020, when 46.5 million packages arrived in Israel, and lower than in 2019, when 61.6 million packages arrived.
However, this year there has been a jump of more than 36% per year in the weight of packages that arrived from abroad.
In 2021, 20,253 tons of products arrived in Israel from abroad, a 36% jump compared to 14,860 tons in 2020, and 16,743 tons in 2019.
Changes in consumption habits
The average weight per package has jumped by 60% in two years, from 272 grams in 2019 to 435 grams in 2021.
The increase in the weight of packages is mainly influenced by two main trends, both on the seller's side and on the buyer's side: the large shopping sites abroad consolidate items into one shipment and no longer ship each product from the "shopping basket" in a separate package.
On the Israeli consumer's side, the fast delivery of deliveries, within a few days of ordering, supports the purchase of more everyday products such as clothing and gifts, which buyers want to receive close to making the purchase.
In 2021, as in 2020 and 2019, the month in which the most packages arrived from abroad with the highest weight and the highest number of items was December, with 4.2 million packages weighing a total of 2,200 tons.
In December, the average weight per package was 524 grams, 20% higher than the annual average weight.
The Black Friday Effect
More packages arrived in December than in any other month, likely due to November's shopping holidays, such as Chinese Singles' Day, Black Friday and Cyber Monday.
The large orders start arriving in Israel between one and two weeks after purchase.
Study: Most Employees in the Economy Are Not Aware of the Possibility of Receiving Tax Refunds
Many employees deserve money from the state, which can reach tens of thousands of shekels.
Have you changed jobs?
Have you gone on unpaid leave?
Did you move from the city to the settlement?
You may be entitled to receive a considerable amount of money in a simple procedure •
All the details - inside
Most employees are not aware of the fact that they are entitled to tax refunds, which can add up to large amounts.
The State Comptroller noted in a report from about two months ago that two million employees are entitled to tax refunds of NIS 3.6 billion, which means that you should also check whether you are eligible to receive tax refunds.
Many employees can receive a high amount, as four out of five employees are eligible for tax refunds.
In practice, on the other hand, several tens of thousands of employees are hired each year.
If you think that these funds will go down the drain anyway, think again: Employees can apply to the IRS for refunds for six years back.
Tax:On conducted an in-depth study of 4,000 of its customers regarding tax refunds during 2020.
The company has over 30,000 customers, so the sample reflects their distribution in terms of population groups and in terms of gender, age, and geography.
The data show that during 2020, due to the outbreak of the COVID-19 crisis and the suspension of hundreds of thousands of workers on unpaid leave, there were a number of significant changes, most notably a 15% increase in the average reimbursement per household, which stood at NIS 4,300 per year.
The reason is that unpaid leave is lower than salaries, and therefore there is a gap between what the employee paid as tax and what he actually needs.
By the way, the highest refund received in 2020 by a customer of the company was NIS 121,054 for repayments over the past 6 years.
What can you get tax refunds for?
One of the reasons to receive tax refunds is a change in the workplace.
81% of people who changed jobs during the year received an average tax refund of NIS 2,943.
Another reason is maternity leave.
The data show that 74% of women who gave birth and were on maternity leave for more than 16 weeks were entitled to a reimbursement of an average of NIS 3,538 for that year
Another reason for a refund is donations.
100% of people who donate and pay taxes have received a refund.
Another factor in the reimbursement is the failure to register credit points for alimony. 63%
The divorcees did not update a credit point for alimony, so the tax refund for each year that such a credit point was not updated is NIS 2,616.
Due to unemployment - unpaid leave: 93% of those who went sick or unemployed and who earned more than NIS 12,000 received a tax refund of NIS 4,021 for that year.
Other reasons for tax refunds are: reimbursement for life insurance payments, life insurance on a mortgage, reimbursement of a qualifying settlement, reimbursement for losses in securities, non-registration of credit points for a man for birth, and distribution of tax refunds according to geographical location.
- 94% of people who deposited for personal life insurance or for taking out a mortgage were eligible for a tax refund.
In an examination conducted on every NIS 1 million on a 25-year mortgage, the cumulative tax refund for the period is over NIS 20,000 for the entire mortgage period
100% of those who move to a qualifying locality received a tax refund for the year of transition, since a certificate of residency in a qualifying locality is given only 12 months after the date the resident becomes a qualifying resident, and thus, in effect, the first year full tax is paid.
79% of the customers holding securities were entitled to a tax refund for the aforementioned years.
However, it is important for those who hold securities to check every year since losses are not rolled over from year to year, but only through the submission of a report.
56% of men who have a child do not write credit points in the year of birth on their paycheck.
The repayment rate can reach tens of thousands of shekels over 6 years.
This is a phenomenon that exists mainly in the Arab sector.
Tax:On CEO, Tal Carmon: "The coronavirus crisis has caused the salaried public in Israel to become much more active.
He is interested, checks and demands what he deserves in income tax refunds.
It turns out that sitting at home, on unpaid leave or after layoffs, for hundreds of thousands of Israelis for many months, has caused many salaried employees to take a closer look at what they are entitled to from the state.
It is important to know that today it is possible to carry out all the procedures for receiving tax refunds digitally, easily and simply, without the bureaucracy that deterred many in the past."
The Employment Market: Fewer Job Applicants, More Wages
AllJobs Report 2021 Summary: At the Top of Demand - Jobs without Experience •
• The number of jobs offered increased by 50%
"Looking for a job, but not storming the market"
In the year that just ended, there was a 15% decline in the number of resumes sent, and an average of only 23 candidates ran for each position, compared to 41 candidates in the previous year, according to a report by the AllJobs website summarizing 2021, on the COVID-19 crisis and its effects on the labor market in Israel.
According to the report, job seekers were mainly interested in jobs such as administration and sales, for which 1,738,485 resumes were sent.
However, jobs without experience led the top of the demand with more than 38,000 searches – apparently due to the return of young people with no professional experience to look for work immediately, at the end of unpaid leave payments.
The number of searches for sales and administration was 35,000 and 32,000 (respectively), drivers and couriers had 11,000 searches, and guarding had a little less than 9,000 searches.
On the other hand, despite the COVID-19 crisis, wages in 2021 increased by 2% compared to 2020, and the average wage in Israel was NIS 11,675 gross.
The average monthly salary in the software field was NIS 17,915, and in information systems analysis it was NIS 17,140.
However, there was a wage gap of more than NIS 2,000 between the center and the periphery: in the center of the country it was NIS 12,500 on average, compared to NIS 10,795 in the north and NIS 10,135 in the south.
In terms of gender, the average wage gap between women and men, which can also be explained by the type of work and the scope of hours, was maintained at 36%.
Men earned NIS 13,295, compared to NIS 9,740 for women.
Trying to get back to the groove
On the business side, there was lateral growth in almost all sectors of the economy, and businesses were eager for working hands.
Thus, the supply of jobs increased by 50% and recorded a record of more than 40,000 jobs at Alljobs.
A survey conducted by the website among employers found that 50% were optimistic about their economic status in 2022, 30% of them indicated their intention to increase total hiring, but 72% understand that they will have difficulty doing so this year.
The largest supply was for jobs with no experience – and there were more than 58,000 of them on the site.
They were followed by customer service and administration positions with about 44,000 jobs in each field, sales and software with 41,000 jobs each, teaching and education with 24,000 vacancies, and warehouse workers still in demand with 19,000 vacancies.
Einav Boimfeld, Director of Research and Content at Alljobs: "Job seekers are trying to get back on track but are not storming the market, mainly due to the lack of attractive jobs in their eyes.
