According to Matanyahu Engelman's report, he recommends "making amendments and improvements in the process of expanding the basket, which will lead to a higher quality utilization of the budget for the health services basket to which the public is entitled."
Throughout the years of the mechanism of addition to the drug basket, in the years 1998-2021, NIS 8 billion was added to the state budget – with the addition ranging from NIS 0 to NIS 500 million each year.
In 2019, 2020, and 2021, requests were submitted to add about 800 new drugs and technologies to the healthcare basket, at a total annual cost of more than NIS 2 billion.
In practice, the budget allocated for the expansion of the basket was smaller than the scope of the requests.
In most of the committee's years of activity (90% of the time), the amount of the budget supplement was less than 1.5% of the health basket, a rate recommended by various committees as the desired additional rate.
The Comptroller notes that it is necessary to examine and regulate the amount of the annual supplement in order to allow for certainty and long-term planning.
Engelman also noted that "the transparency model in the basket's work is deficient."
Thus, for example, the Basket Committee's work procedure stipulates that the minutes of the meetings, which are closed to the public, will be published within 60 days, but in practice the minutes are published with a delay of 109-160 days, while sometimes the minutes of the final meetings are not published at all.
"The delay in the publication of the minutes harms the transparency of the decisions; As a result, the ability of the bidders – patient organizations and pharmaceutical companies – to submit reapplications as soon as possible and relevant, may be impaired, after they have learned lessons from the rejection of their proposals, analyzed the reasons for their failure in the previous round, improved and revised their proposals, and re-evaluated the feasibility of accepting them in the next round," the comptroller noted in the report.
"The Ministry of Health must publish the protocols in accordance with the timetables set out in the procedure."
Out of thousands of submissions, only one economic comment was submitted
Another criticism by Engelman relates to a preliminary process of evaluating the technologies submitted to the drug basket.
The State Comptroller found that about half (46%) of the technologies submitted did not pass this stage, but the Ministry of Health does not publish the reasons for the postponement.
Another flaw concerns the activities of the Drug Basket Subcommittee, which is closed to the media and the public, and in which patient numbers and the costs of medications are discussed.
The Comptroller recommends adding a public representative or examining the possibility of publishing the discussions to the public without confidential commercial details.
The procedure according to which the Health Services Basket Committee operates stipulates that "an economic assessment must be submitted" to a request to add a drug to the basket.
But in practice, over the years, only one economic assessment has been submitted out of thousands of submissions – and the committee makes its decisions without an economic assessment.
For example, requests were submitted to the Basket Committee's deliberations for the years 2019-2021 to add anti-obesity drugs to the basket.
The report found that the requests did not include economic estimates, including an estimate of the amount that could have been saved due to reducing the damage caused by diseases caused by obesity or due to the ability to avoid gastric bypass surgeries.
It also appears that the decisions of the Drug Basket Committee are not in line with the goals and strategy of the Ministry of Health.
Thus, for example, in 2019, the Ministry of Health defined preventive medicine and preparedness for the treatment of tumors in chronic diseases as goals, but in the framework of the decisions regarding the expansion of the basket, no emphasis was placed on the need to achieve these goals.
The Comptroller also warns that since 2011, the basket includes services that are not the responsibility of the HMOs, including rehabilitation and mobility devices and various vaccines, which are provided by the Ministry of Health (the "Third Addendum").
This is when the legal framework for this step is regulated only retroactively.
In the past six years, NIS 74 million of the addition to the drug basket has been used for these services.
Engelman recommends that the Ministry of Health update the procedures for the basket work and also determine whether there is a need for a separate financial supplement for these services.
About a third of the new drugs that are included in the drug basket are defined as "drugs at no additional cost", the use of which does not cost the HMOs an additional amount because they replace an existing treatment.
The Comptroller proposes to examine the possibility of these medications being discussed in a different and shortened track, so that it will be possible to update the medication basket several times a year and not just once a year.
There is no supervision of the use of extremely expensive drugs.
The audit also shows that since the work of the basket committee began 20 years ago, the Ministry of Health has not asked the health plans to report and has not supervised the scope of uses and utilization of the medications in the basket, information that could have allowed the ministry to analyze and audit the budget given to the health plans.
Over the years, only two reports have been published relating to the years 2006-2009, and these too were published considerably late (the last was published this year and dealt with the use of the budget in the years 2007-2009).
"The delay in conducting tests may lead to difficulty in collecting and analyzing the data, irrelevance of the conclusions that arise from the examination after such a long period, to the subcommittee's sub-optimal pricing and to making decisions based on inconclusive findings," the report states.
In addition, the Ministry does not audit and supervise the use of particularly expensive drugs and has not learned any lessons.
These are 10 drugs that accounted for 62% of the addition to the basket (NIS 1.7 billion in 2016-2021).
The comptroller wrote: "It is recommended that the Ministry of Health conduct individual controls on these drugs and technologies and analyze the scope of their use against the estimates.
Controls and analysis will make it possible to draw systemic conclusions about the work process of the basket committee and the subcommittee, and on the manner in which estimates are prepared when pricing drugs and technologies and improve them."
