Suspicion of Wolfson's failure: The surgeon caused a rupture in the heart - and the patient died.
This is the first procedure performed by Dr. Firas Abu Aker as the director of the Thoracic Surgery Unit at the hospital.
The chairman of the doctors' committee complained that the director, Dr. Engel, had been warned before his appointment
Hospital: "He is valued and experienced"
First publication: A horrific mistake occurred at the Wolfson Government Hospital in Holon, when during the operation the doctor made a tear in the patient's heart, which led to his tragic death.
The surgery on an 83-year-old lung cancer patient was performed on April 19.
This was the first surgery performed by Dr. Firas Abu Aker at the hospital, after he was appointed director of the Thoracic Surgery Unit at Wolfson.
During the surgery, which was intended to drain the area surrounding the patient's heart, the surgeon accidentally caused a large rupture in the heart, which led to severe bleeding and caused the patient's death.
However, the unusual complication opened a Pandora's box, which raised difficult questions regarding the management of the hospital.
The director of the Oncology Institute and chairman of the doctors' committee, Dr. Ronen Brenner, demanded an investigation into the affair in a letter he sent to the hospital's director, Dr. Anat Engel.
In the letter, he raised very serious allegations about Dr. Engel's conduct and the appointment of Dr. Abu Aker, after the previous director of the unit, Dr. Benny Zuckerman, moved to Sheba Hospital in Tel Hashomer.
A huge hole in the heart
According to Dr. Brenner's letter, the patient was lucid, functioning and had been treated by him for the past four years.
Recently, he has had an outbreak of the disease, and an abnormal accumulation of fluid has been discovered within the heart membrane, which contains the heart muscle.
Also, the surgeon, Dr. Abu Aker, was under the impression that he could perform the surgery.
According to the complaint, there was a serious malfunction in the operation, and Dr. Hagai Dekel, director of the Department of Cardiothoracic Surgery at Wolfson, who was operating on a child in the next room at the time, "was rushed to the operating table and saw a huge hole in the heart."
According to him, the heart was drained of blood, the blood pressures were negligible, and the surgical approach was wrong.
In addition, Dr. Brenner said that Dr. Dekel contacted him and told him that Dr. Abu Aker was not professionally and personally suitable to manage the Wolfson Thoracic Surgery Unit.
However, despite his explicit warnings and despite the fact that he was supposed to be the direct manager of the breast surgeon, Dr. Engel executed a tender without involving him and accepted Dr. Abu Aker for the position.
He added: "This is an uncomplicated process, which lasted a few minutes," and added: "It is impossible not to relate to the flawed process of accepting Dr. Abu Aker to the position.
The question arises as to whether Engel is directly responsible for the failure of the operation and the patient's death."
Experienced Surgeon
Information and claims by other senior doctors were presented to Israel Hayom, which corroborate the questions raised by Dr. Ronen Brenner.
Dr. Mordechai Shimonov, director of Surgery A at Wolfson, responded to Brenner's complaint, writing that Dr. Abu Aker is "one of the most experienced surgeons in the country, but a relatively young thoracic surgeon."
He added that he was selected in a proper tender and that Dr. Dekel did not take part in it, in accordance with his declarations of his desire to "disconnect" from the chest unit.
He added: "I was not a party to the process either, and I may have been supposed to.
Dr. Shimonov wrote that Dr. Firas Abu Aker began working on April 10 and is entitled to 100 days of grace, "All the doctors at the hospital were impressed by his professionalism and his motivation and willingness to work.
He has already performed dozens of similar procedures, and unfortunately the current case ended as it did in an unfortunate way.
Wolfson Hospital said in response: "We share the family's grief.
This is a patient of the oncologist Dr. Ronen Brenner.
The thoracic surgeon mentioned in the article is a respected surgeon with many years of experience, and was selected in a tender to manage a thoracic surgery unit affiliated with the surgery department at Wolfson Hospital.
"According to Dr. Hagai Dekel, his words that were quoted are inaccurate and were taken out of context.
It should be noted that this is a patient who was unfortunately in a very serious condition.
The hospital is examining the details of the case transparently, and the Ministry of Health is familiar with the details of the case."
