A Model for Healing: Three Senior Doctors Talk About Their Mentors
Prof. Galia Rahav misses the wit and wisdom of the late Prof. Marvin Shapira, especially during the days of the pandemic •
Dr. Shlomi Kodesh does not forget, even from the height of his position, the push from the late Prof. Shaul Sukenik •
and Dr. Efrat Baron-Harlev thanks Dr. Tommy Sheinfeld for the lesson in empathizing with the patients •
Three key people in hospitals write about those who inspired and encouraged them to be better, both as therapists and as human beings.
Three senior doctors, three teachers of life and the profession: On the occasion of Israeli Doctor's Day, Israel Hayom invited Prof. Galia Rahav, Dr. Shlomi Kodesh and Dr. Efrat Baron-Harlev to recall the figures who accompanied them at the beginning of their journey – and helped them become who they are today.
Prof. Galia Rahav, Director of the Infectious Diseases Unit at Sheba |
About Prof. Marvin Shapira z"l
The encounter that opened my eyes - and changed my life
If I hadn't met the late Prof. Marvin Shapira, who was the director of the Infectious Diseases Unit at Hadassah Hospital, I probably would have remained a physician specializing in internal medicine.
He is the one who made me love the field of infectious diseases and influenced me to work in it.
I met him in the corridors of Hadassah, back in the 1980s.
I didn't think for a moment that I would leave the internal medicine, as I loved the treatment of the patient himself; But Prof. Shapira showed me that the field of infectious diseases is also expressed in neurology, in internal medicine, and in virtually every field.
I thank him for bringing me to this field.
All along, I liked his investigative approach, an approach that gets to the root of the problem.
The discussions with him were analytical and logical.
He was a doctor with all his soul, who loved the patients and taught me not to take things for granted and to examine everything in depth.
He was a real and honest person, devoid of ego, qualities that I liked very much about him.
Initially, when I was asked to choose a doctor who was a role model for me and influenced me the most, I intended to choose my father, the late Dr. Yosef Rakover, a Holocaust survivor who served as a doctor in a partisan unit.
He was an amazing doctor, who influenced me to go to medicine – but he also reminds me of Marvin Shapira.
Both, for example, coined proverbs that doctors use to this day – for example, "tissue is de Ichio", that is, taking a biopsy of tissue from the affected organ makes it possible to know which medications should be given; Or "Won Yo Huz It, Yo Luz It," which is meant to explain that antibiotic overuse leads to bacteria becoming resistant to it.
The late Prof. Shapira was married to a physiotherapist who worked at Hadassah and was the father of two daughters.
He passed away about a year ago, and when I visited his family at Shiva, I cried.
He was something – a witty and clever epidemiologist who volunteered for everything.
He never complained, not even during his serious illness.
He was one of the first doctors on the team to deal with epidemics, and he was sorely missed during this period.
Had he been with us today, I am sure I would have consulted with him, and I am sure that he would have been one of the leaders of the team dealing with epidemics.
Published by: Meital Yassur Beit-Or
Dr. Shlomi Kodesh, Director of Soroka Hospital |
About Prof. Shaul Sukenik z"l
A teacher and friend who supported me and raised generations of doctors
.
I first met the late Prof. Shaul Sukenik when I was a fourth-year medical student, and I came to a round of internal medicine in the internal medicine department that he directed.
Later, I returned to the department in my sixth year, and I did my medical school thesis under his supervision, writing a computer simulation of a patient with polyarthritis (inflammation of multiple joints).
Shaul influenced every significant juncture in my professional life over the course of 20 years, and was the most significant man in shaping my image as a doctor; Not only professionally, but also – and especially – from a personal and human point of view.
During my internship, I debated between family medicine and internal medicine, and I consulted with him about choosing a specialty.
In the end, I chose to specialize in internal medicine with him at Soroka.
During my internship, he provided me with constant guidance, in a variety of avenues – in scientific writing (sorry Shaul, I wasn't persistent enough), in communication with patients, in working in a multidisciplinary team – a field in which the department excelled – and in fact, in every aspect related to medicine.
To this day, I recognize in me, as a doctor and as a manager, characteristics that come from Shaul.
When I finished my internship and was debating whether to go for a period of study abroad, Shaul pushed and directed me, and helped me with letters of recommendation and advice on how to proceed.
The training period was a very important period for my professional development, and without Shaul's support and push, it is not certain that this would have happened.
When I returned, when I received an offer to join the hospital's management, Shaul was again the one who supported and assisted.
Later on, we passed through complex periods together in the Division of Internal Medicine.
Shaul knew how to integrate the teacher, principal, friend and teammate in a wonderful way, without his various roles interfering with each other.
I aspire to succeed like him in this special combination.
He raised generations of students, interns and interns, who are now throughout the medical system in Israel, and whose excellent work commemorates his memory and work.
I am honored to be part of this group.
Published by: Ilya Yagorov
Dr. Efrat Baron-Harlev, Director of Schneider Children's Medical Center |
About Dr. Tommy Sheinfeld
The man who taught me medicine, and especially listening.
Dr. Tommy Sheinfeld, founder and former director of the Intensive Care Unit at Schneider Children's Medical Center, taught me to be an ICU, but more than that, he taught me to think.
The obvious thing I learned from him is to take care of the most complex, the sickest children.
The children, some of whom were healthy just a moment ago, are now between life and death.
The obvious is to have very difficult conversations, perhaps the most difficult, with families who never imagined they would find themselves in these complex situations in the intensive care unit with their children.
Sounds strange, but it's the obvious.
But I learned even more significant and profound things from him.
Looking back, since I'm a doctor who runs and a manager who is a doctor, it's clear to me today that the connection between the worlds is clear; The education I received from Dr. Sheinfeld connects them.
Dr. Sheinfeld taught me to listen attentively to many things: to listen to the children, to listen to the monitor, to listen to the nurses, to the care teams, both young and old, and to listen to the parents.
All of this needs to be done not only to communicate more correctly and more successfully, but to constantly gather a lot of information that can prevent the next deterioration.
Preventive processes in the treatment of children exist everywhere, and of course also in intensive care.
Listening and dialogue stimulate a deeper understanding, both on the part of the treating staff and on the part of the patients and their families.
My understanding today as a manager is that these insights are also true when looking at an entire system.
The deeper and more rigorous an understanding exists, which incorporates all the parties involved in the discourse, the more precise the decision-making process will be, adapted to the situation, and most importantly – early enough to prevent future damage, immediate or distant.
That's why Dr. Tommy Sheinfeld is so much more than an inspiring character for me.
He's a person who taught me a lot of medicine, but mostly taught me to think fast and precisely, to listen – and then to apply.
