Medical Malpractice in the Different Stages of Labor
In order to receive compensation, the plaintiffs must prove, in addition to the negligence, that the damage was caused by that negligence
Childbirth is one of the happiest and most exciting events in a family's life.
Unfortunately, however, sometimes births end in severe damage caused to the mother or newborn as a result of the negligence of the medical staff.
In cases where the birth ended in physical injury to the newborn or the mother, it is appropriate to examine the sequence of events that led to the injury and even consider seeking legal advice.
A lawyer specializing in the field of medical malpractice will examine whether there were defects in the conduct of the medical staff during the various stages of labor that caused the damage, and if he sees fit, he will consult with a medical expert in the relevant field.
It should be emphasized that not every mistake in treatment on the part of the medical staff amounts to negligence (in the legal sense of this term) and that various complications during the birth do not necessarily indicate that the management was negligent.
When, then, is it negligence?
When the doctor's mistake stemmed from a lack of skill or deviated from the reasonable level of care, and the lack of skill and deviation from the accepted level of care caused damage to the patient that would not have been caused had the doctor not acted in this way.
In this article, we will examine the different stages of labor, explain what complications may occur in each of the stages, and when they amount to medical malpractice.
The contraction stage
The contraction phase lasts an average of 8 to 14 hours.
At this stage, the cervix is gradually opened (in order to allow the passage of the fetus during birth) and at the end of the process it should reach a diameter of about 10 centimeters.
Most cases of medical negligence during the labor stage deal with the failure to identify fetal distress prior to birth, which caused damage to the newborn, which sometimes even manifests itself in cerebral palsy.
Cerebral palsy (CP):
Cerebral palsy may be caused by failure to identify or delay in identifying prenatal asphyxiation, which is expressed in a failure to supply oxygen to the fetus's brain tissue.
In general, monitoring the mother's condition and correctly interpreting the monitor that monitors the fetal heart activity should lead to early identification of the development of fetal distress, which allows the medical staff to act quickly and rescue the newborn before it is irreversibly damaged.
Cases in which the medical staff ignores signs that indicate that the fetus is suffering from a lack of oxygen, or that the staff does not correctly interpret the data before it, especially the fetal monitor, or responds late to the distress expressed in the monitor – may constitute negligence.
Cerebral palsy may also be caused by the prolapse of the umbilical cord as well as as by a rupture in the uterus that was not identified in time.
Even in these difficult events, it is worth clarifying whether the medical staff acted properly.
For example, Adv. Anna Reif Liganza, of Caspi Sror & Co., which specializes in representing victims of medical malpractice, says that her firm handled a claim by a child who was injured during childbirth after the midwife rupture the amniotic sac when the fetus's head was too high, thus causing the umbilical cord to prolapse (when the umbilical cord precedes the fetus's head) and impairing the oxygen supply to the fetal brain (as a result of the pressure of the fetus's head on the umbilical cord) and causing it to be born with severe neurological damage.
In another case, the attorney said that her office filed a lawsuit due to severe medical negligence on the part of the staff of the maternity ward at a large hospital, which during the birth did not identify clear signs at the time that necessitated a real suspicion that the mother was suffering from a rupture of the uterus in the area of the surgical scar of her previous pregnancy.
The fetus, which was expelled through the tear in its mother's uterus into the abdominal cavity, suffered from severe fetal distress until it was rescued at a late stage when it was on the verge of death.
Due to the severe fetal suffering during his birth, the child suffered a complex neurological disability.
It should be emphasized that in order to be entitled to compensation, the plaintiffs must prove, in addition to negligence, that there is a causal connection between the negligence of the medical staff that led to the failure to identify the asphyxiation and the damage caused to the newborn, i.e., that the damage was caused by such negligence and not by any other reason or cause.
The examination of the causal relationship will be carried out by examining medical indices, which, according to the medical literature, only if they exist does there exist a causal link between asphyxia and brain injury.
Among other things, measures of the pH level in the fetus's blood, its Apgar scores, the existence of neurological and systemic damage, and more are examined.
Death of the fetus
The stage of active labor
The active birth stage begins when the opening of the cervix reaches a diameter of 10 centimeters and ends with the birth of the baby.
Unfortunately, most medical complications occur during this critical stage.
Delay in Delivery and Avoidance of Cesarean Sections
In some cases, dysfunctional birth develops, i.e., a lack of progress in the active birth process.
In such situations, it is customary to perform a cesarean section, in order to prevent various damages that may be caused to the fetus due to the delay in birth.
"There are cases in which failure to perform a cesarean section on time may cause irreversible damage to the fetus," Adv. Reif-Leganza explained to us.
"For example, we conducted a medical malpractice claim for the death of a child caused by a significant delay in performing a cesarean section.
Contrary to any known medical practice, the medical staff were not able to identify the fetal distress and perform a cesarean section despite the extremely slow progress of the birth.
The delay in performing the surgery caused multi-system damage to the newborn, which ultimately led to her death shortly after her birth."
Negligence in a vacuum birth
In situations where the mother or the fetus is in significant danger that requires a particularly quick termination of labor, a vacuum birth is sometimes performed.
In this process, a "dome" is attached to the fetus's head using a vacuum and the fetus is pulled out by force.
Naturally, this action involves dangers and may cause damage to both the fetus and the mother, and therefore requires great caution, precision and skill.
In these events, medical negligence may manifest itself in the fact that the doctor does not adhere to the mandatory instructions and performs the operation despite the existence of a contraindication, such as when the fetus's head is too high in the pelvis, or when it is performed for a longer time than allowed, or when despite the failure of a large number of attempts, the doctor continues to repeat the operation more than the permitted number of attempts.
In these cases, if the negligent vacuum action caused damage to the newborn – among other things, it may cause cranial damage and bleeding that may cause the development of brain damage – there is room to file a tort claim.
ERB paralysis
Ambush paralysis is a congenital nerve injury to the brachial plexus (a nerve junction that connects the spine to the upper part of the shoulder) and when it occurs during childbirth, it is worth checking whether the damage occurred as a result of the negligence of the obstetric staff.
The injury manifests itself in the weakness of the muscles of the hand and can reach complete paralysis of the entire arm.
This paralysis is often caused by difficulty in removing the newborn due to the occurrence of 'shoulder spraxia' – a midwifery emergency that occurs when the fetus's shoulders are trapped inside the birth canal after its head has come out.
When should you suspect that the paralysis was caused by medical negligence?
In cases where the fetus's weight assessment indicated that it was a macrosomal fetus, meaning that it is expected to be born weighing more than 4.5 kilograms, and in accordance with the guidelines, it is preferable to deliver the mother by cesarean section.
When the weight of the newborn is over 4 kilograms, a cesarean section should be considered in light of the risk factors, including gestational diabetes and prolongation of the second stage of labor.
In the event that the medical staff ignores an abnormal weight assessment of the fetus or other risk factors and chooses to continue with a vaginal birth and the risk of shoulder dislocation and ERB paralysis is realized, there is a reasonable possibility that it is medical negligence.
Indeed, in CA 2694/90, the Supreme Court ruled that "the risk that shoulder stenosis will occur during childbirth can be predicted in advance with one degree or another of accuracy, and the way to prevent shoulder stenosis, where there is concern about its occurrence, is to perform a cesarean section."
Placental exit stage
The separation of the placenta from the uterus and its exit occurs due to the contraction of the uterus after the birth of the newborn and is accompanied by bleeding.
In most cases, the process lasts up to half an hour from the moment the baby comes out and usually occurs spontaneously, without the involvement of the medical staff.
After the placenta comes out, the medical team will check whether it has come out intact or whether parts of the placenta remain in the uterus.
As part of this stage, complications may occur that may cause serious damage to the mother.
One of the well-known complications as a result of placental residues in the uterus is called "Asherman's syndrome", scarring of the uterine wall as a result of inflammation caused by the residue of the placenta in the uterus, a phenomenon that damages the uterine lining in a way that does not allow the pregnancy to be implanted.
Therefore, in cases where the medical staff did not identify that placental remnants were left or did not take all measures to prevent damage to the uterine lining, despite the suspicion of placental remnants in the uterus, it may be medical negligence and the case deserves an in-depth examination by an experienced lawyer in the field.
Death of the mother
The death of a woman during childbirth is quite rare.
In these cases, the event that was supposed to bring happiness and joy of life to the whole family becomes, unfortunately, the most tragic event for her.
In some cases, the medical staff does not detect bleeding in the mother on time or reacts late to such bleeding.
"For example...", Adv. Reif-Liganza told us, "Our firm filed a lawsuit concerning the death of a mother, when in that case the medical staff ignored and did not respond to the mother's worrying vital signs, for many hours, and delayed diagnosing massive and uncontrollable bleeding that occurred as a known complication of the underlying disease from which she suffered."
"In another case...", said Adv. Reif-Liganza, "our firm represented the relatives of a woman who gave birth after giving birth to twins due to bleeding that originated from the incision of the cesarean section that was not suture properly.
In that case, the mother complained of severe pain and weakness after the operation, but the medical staff did not properly address her complaints and her clinical condition, reacting late only after her body systems began to collapse, which led to her death."
Uterine loss
In severe cases, medical negligence in childbirth may lead to a hysterectomy, says Adv. Rafe Lingza: "Our firm has conducted a lawsuit against a hospital based on hysterectomy due to medical negligence after birth.
In that case, the mother, a 31-year-old woman, lost her uterus due to a lack of proper treatment for the massive bleeding observed by the medical staff after the birth, and despite this, no measures were taken during the time that could have prevented the damage."
What are the compensation awarded in claims for medical negligence in childbirth?
Compensation for a newborn for injury due to medical negligence in childbirth includes many components of damage, with the most significant amounts being given for pain and suffering, nursing and paid care, loss of wages and pensions for the victim and even to his parents, and other damage components.
The compensation awarded to an injured minor for wage and pension losses is calculated in most cases on the basis of the average wage in the economy.
In addition, the compensation also includes medical expenses, the cost of medical and rehabilitation equipment, the cost of adapting housing to the baby's needs, mobility, and more.
"The amount of compensation is determined in each case on its own merits and according to its circumstances," says Adv. Reif-Liganza, and she adds that "today most claims on the grounds of medical malpractice end in a compromise that weighs the chance and risk that each party has in conducting the proceeding," but the attorney added that "there are cases in which the proceeding ends only with a judgment, and then if the claim is not rejected, the plaintiffs will receive full compensation for all their damages, for example,  As part of a lawsuit conducted by our firm, the District Court awarded compensation to a minor who suffered cerebral palsy due to a delay in identifying fetal distress in excess of NIS 10 million."
In conclusion
Medical malpractice in childbirth is undoubtedly the nightmare of every family.
In these cases, a proper legal examination of the sequence of events that caused the tragic outcome, by an attorney skilled in managing claims on the grounds of medical malpractice, can help you win the compensation you deserve.
This is the reason for the prevalence of keratoconus eye disease in the south
Research has shown that there is a link between the development of the disease and intimate marriage.
• The highest prevalence was found in the Bedouin sector.
Expert: "It is possible that in any sector with a lot of weddings between cousins, a high incidence of the disease has been found."
Keratoconus is an inherited eye disease that causes several visual impairments.
It is very important to diagnose it as soon as possible, and to find the right solutions to prevent the situation from getting worse.
In recent years, several studies have been conducted to help understand how the disease develops, and innovative treatments have been developed.
The new studies provide a research basis for the suspicion that keratoconus eye disease is a genetic disease.
A recent study on the transformation of the shape of the cornea from a dome to a cone, revealed that the cause of the disease, the weakness of the cornea and its deformity is related to an enzymatic imbalance, as a result of which free radicals can damage the proteins in the cornea - and its structure will change.
The source of this lack of enzymes is genetic, a fact that strengthens the hypothesis that keratocanus is an inherited disease.
According to Prof. Ariella Gordon-Shag, head of the Department of Optometry Sciences at Hadassah Academic College, "In a study published in the field among Arab students in Haifa, the prevalence of keratoconus was found to be 3.2%.
The highest prevalence was among students from the Bedouin sector – 20% had keratoconus, but there was a relatively small sample."
The researcher added that this is not a surprising finding: "There is a high prevalence of keratoconus in the Bedouin sector.
In our studies, we found that close marriage is a risk factor for keratoconus disease.
Thus, in any sector with a lot of weddings between cousins, we may find a high incidence."
In this context, it should be noted that this is an important finding in light of the unequivocal conclusion: in cases where a family history of keratoconus disease appears, all family members should go for an appropriate eye exam as soon as possible.
According to Arza Fruchter, a B.Sc clinical optometrist, "There are ten times more visits to the clinic from remote peripheral areas, especially from the south, compared to the center."
Fruchter adds, "In the past decade, I have noticed that most of the patients come from the periphery, especially from the Be'er Sheva area.
This is mainly due to the high prevalence of marriages within the family (especially in the Bedouin sector) and various allergies, and a lack of awareness of the proper treatment of the problem."
So how is the disease diagnosed?
Fruchter explains that keratoconus usually develops in adolescence or in the late teens (ages 15-16 or 20).
The disease includes a decrease in vision, in parallel with an increase in the cylinder.
Keratoconus patients attest to distorted and/or blurred vision of figures and objects.
These signs worsen with the development of the disease, which usually develops slowly and gradually over the years.
However, the disease may also develop at a rapid pace and reach its peak in just a few months.
Many patients even report increased sensitivity to light.
