Senior police official: "What is needed here is a government policy and setting goals"
The Israel Police has launched an operation to eradicate the phenomenon of illegal aliens, but there is still a long way to go.
There is no single entity in the State of Israel today that integrates this whole issue."
"If we want to deal with the phenomenon of illegal aliens, a government policy is required, from which goals, tasks and responsibilities must be derived.
Today, there is not a single entity in the State of Israel that integrates this whole issue," a senior police official told Israel Hayom.
Until a month and a half ago, before the escalation of the security situation, the phenomenon was manifested in about 20,000 to 30,000 undocumented immigrants entering the fence every day.
In addition, between 100,000 and 110,000 Palestinians with work permits enter Israel every day through 34 supervised crossings.
It should be noted that Palestinians have been employed in Israel since the end of the Six-Day War, and the number of permits in each industry is limited by the quota set by the political echelon in accordance with the security, economic, and political situation in the State of Israel.
The permits are issued by the IDF through the Coordination and Liaison Administration.
In light of this, undocumented immigrants are not necessarily Palestinians whose entry is prohibited due to criminal involvement or connection to attacks, but in many cases they are Palestinians whose entry is prohibited because they do not meet the permitted permit quota.
It should be emphasized that those who carried out the attacks in Ariel, Dizengoff and Elad were considered undocumented terrorists, but they were not supervised, because they had not previously committed any criminal offense that required the security forces to supervise their movements.
"Therefore, there is no significance for them to enter through breaches in the fence," says a senior security source, "Anyone who wants to carry out an attack can also enter the country through the supervised crossings, and there have been such cases in the past.
Thousands of arrests
Following the attack in Elad and in light of the numerous warnings of terror attacks, the police launched a large-scale operation to locate illegal aliens.
By the end of the week, about 16,000 undocumented immigrants had been arrested.
Of these, about 600 were interrogated and criminal cases were opened, and about 200 were imprisoned.
According to police prosecution policy, proceedings against an illegal alien are carried out only against repeat offenders or people who repeat the act repeatedly (recidivists).
An illegal alien who was arrested for the first time is interrogated, documented and returned to the Occupied Territories.
Sometimes this is repeated the second time, but only the third time is he arrested, imprisoned, and indicted for illegal presence.
According to the law, if an illegal alien is caught within a range of about 50 to 100 meters from each side of the separation fence, he is dealt with by the military prosecution.
Data obtained by Israel Hayom shows that in 2021, the police dealt with 40,010 illegal aliens, transporters and lodgers.
7,405 illegal aliens were arrested and 19,533 criminal cases were opened.
The number of employers, transporters and complainers handled by the police in 2021 was 6,537.
469 were arrested, and 5,640 criminal cases were opened.
"The foundations of the undocumented phenomenon do not depend on the police, not on the IDF, not on Israeli society and on Palestinian society.
They depend on other factors," says a senior law enforcement official.
"In order to deal with the phenomenon, their motivation to go out to work in Israel must be uprooted, and the Israeli side must exact a price from them that will prevent them from crossing the fence.
Sources involved in the matter claim that the non-collection of the price is due, among other things, to a lack of places of detention and to the fact that arrests are made only when there are accompanying offenses or when there are recidivists.
Legal sources claim that the decision to charge the price of the unpaid security bond was made, among other things, because the courts cannot cope with the number of arrests made every day.
Anyone who examines the punishment will find that it is not deterrent."
There is great complexity
"He is a complex person," says a police source.
He could be the father of a family who came to Israel to work in order to earn a few shekels and come back.
This is the basic platform, on which many types of undocumented persons who enter the country to commit criminal offenses or carry out terror attacks are dressed."
The undocumented person can be an adult or a minor.
In the past, 16-year-olds were caught by the police illegally, and even children aged 8 and 10 were sent by their parents to intersections on the roads, in order to earn a few shekels a day from drivers.
"It also makes the matter complicated, because in such cases we have to bring the parents and indict them for neglect," says a senior police officer.
Most Palestinians are employed in Israel as manual laborers.
The most unusual are electrical work or advanced construction work.
In the past, there were also local authorities that employed undocumented people in garbage disposal, mainly in the north.
Out of 34 crossings, there are about 18 main crossings.
There are crossings of vehicles and goods, there are crossings through which only people pass, and there are crossings that are both.
All crossings are supervised by the IDF and the Crossings Authority.
The undocumented people are usually transported into the country by private drivers, as they are easy money.
"There are those who do this for a living and there are gangs whose main occupation is transporting undocumented people," says a senior police official, "Usually most of them are Israeli Arabs, who speak the same language and correspond with them.
It can reach 100 shekels to 300 shekels per person.
Registered companies don't deal with this, because if the company is caught, it is doomed to close."
The police emphasize that under certain conditions, transporting undocumented vehicles can be considered an offense.
"A taxi driver who works with licenses in accordance with licenses and insurances, who collects Palestinians at designated points and at fixed hours, including an orderly reservation, is not breaking the law," says a senior police official, "Anyone who knows that he is transporting illegal aliens usually picks them up in the middle of the night at hiding points, including dropping off at hidden spots.
Most of these guys drive a car from Chokmak because they know that their car is being stolen, so they prefer to drive in an old car."
