Study determines: Zoom meetings hurt creativity
About 2,100 engineers and academics around the world were asked to develop solutions to the problem – some in video meetings, some in face-to-face meetings.
The result: a virtual meeting harms creativity and out-of-the-box thinking.
Columbia University Research Leader: "The visual focus on the screen impairs the idea generation process" •
Nechama Porta: There is no harm to work productivity or critical thinking.
A large scientific study recently published in the scientific journal Nature examined the effect of video meetings on the creativity of their participants, compared to face-to-face meetings.
Unfortunately, creativity has been found to be impaired in virtual meetings through screens.
The research question, led by Melanie Brooks, an assistant professor at Columbia University, was whether remote computer-assisted meetings preserve the creativity that exists in office brainstorming sessions, or whether the level of creativity and free thinking decreases as a result of distance.
The study itself began in 2016 but received a major boost during the two years of COVID-19, during which many employees switched to working from home.
"People in an in-person meeting move around the room, use objects and use them to think creatively," Brooks says.
"In a computer session, on the other hand, the concentration in maintaining eye contact with others comes at the expense of creative activity in the brain.
The visual focus on the screen reduces cognition.
People are more focused on video when interacting, which hurts the broader and expansive idea generation process."
The space is reduced.
To test the results of the experiment and see if they would be repeated, they were tested twice—once at Columbia University and once in real life—on engineers who knew each other from an early acquaintance.
At the university, the researcher divided a group of 602 faculty members and students into two parts – in one the subjects were asked to meet in person and develop solutions to the problem, and in the second, they were asked to do so through a computer.
At the same time, 1,490 engineers from five countries in Europe, the Middle East and South Asia were asked to share a similar pattern and solve a problem presented to them in a new way.
In both cases, a decrease in creativity and out-of-the-box thinking was found among those who met virtually.
Jay Olson, a postdoctoral fellow at McGill University in Canada and a researcher who deals with ways to measure creativity, was not involved in the study but was not surprised by the results.
In his opinion, as part of a thinking activity, people usually look at their surroundings to help generate ideas, whereas in a video meeting, the thinking converges on the screen and does not expand in a way that allows for creativity.
"When the people are in the same room, they look around them and see the space, where there are objects and situations that can evoke new associations in them.
On the other hand, research shows that computer-generated relationships change our attention so that we are more focused inward and on the screen, and this way reduces innovation and the generation of ideas by looking at the environment and thinking outward."
There is no harm to critical thinking.
However, before managers run employees back into the office, the researchers note that "working through a computer did not harm productivity itself or people's critical thinking about innovative proposals, when they had to choose the best idea from a set of ideas.
In other words, the damage is focused only on creativity and not on other forms of working in front of a computer."
Prof. Alan Langer, a professor of psychology at Harvard University, also qualifies the findings.
According to her, "There's a difference between just creativity, like new uses for Frisbee (one of the research questions; A.G.) and solutions of work.
It's also possible that when employees are more relaxed after getting to know each other, or when they're working from home, creativity will improve."
Both Prof. Langer and Dr. Olson have also proposed future research in which such meetings would be interrupted into thinking states and wandering around the room to see how this activity would affect the final outcome.
