We checked: What do the side effects after the COVID-19 vaccine mean?
Many people who get vaccinated feel weak, fever and fatigue after receiving the shot, while others do not feel anything.
Could this indicate a stronger immune system of those who do experience these symptoms, or is it a baseless rumor?
As more and more people get vaccinated, the lack of information about the side effects continues to confuse and create rumors, most of which are untrue.
Is the immune system of those who developed side effects stronger than those whose bodies responded less harshly to the vaccine, which may prove that their system is unable to fight off a foreign body that enters the body?
"There are several levels of reactions to the vaccine," says Dr. David Dvir, head of the Primary Medicine Division at Meuhedet and a member of the Advisory Committee for Epidemic Response Team, and reassuring: "Headaches, fatigue, pain in the spot, these are the immediate reactions of the immune system.
This is how the body reacts when a foreign entity enters the system."
Is there a connection between the levels of antibodies developed and the side effects?
"There is no correlation between the feelings and the development of antibodies against the virus.
About 50-60% feel the side effects, but about 90% develop protection against the virus.
It was not found that people who developed strong responses were more protected."
"In the medical literature, there is no correlation between immediate response and the level of vaccination.
In some of the trials in which people were also given placebo vaccines, about a quarter of them developed headaches.
It is also a mental component – how the person perceives the vaccine, if he expects there to be side effects.
Many of the phenomena that happen could have happened normally, but since the public has been vaccinated, it attributes the response to the vaccine itself, and this is a bias that we see regarding vaccines in general – attributing phenomena that happen close to the vaccine and are attributed to it."
According to Dr. Dvir, the causes of the commonly reported symptoms, such as weakness and headaches, are not yet known.
Regarding myocarditis, opinions are divided.
"There are all kinds of theories on the subject, but it should be noted that the virus itself causes higher rates of myocarditis than the vaccine.
One of the theories is that it's a strong immune response."
Is it even possible to assess the strength of an immune system?
"When students were exposed to the flu virus, they showed that those who didn't sleep or were under higher stress were more vulnerable to infection.
Apart from that, there are laboratory parameters that test the immune system or its components.
When there is a decrease in the immune system, you see it immediately.
People get a lot of viral or infectious diseases.
It's not like someone walks around with a weakened immune system and isn't aware of it.
These are people who come to inquiries because of recurring events of infectious diseases, and what affects the system are banal things: stress, diet, sleep.
By the way, we also don't want an overly strong immune system, because it can cause autoimmune diseases."
MRNA vaccines will soon appear in additional contexts, thanks to the vast knowledge that has accumulated about them in recent times.
"There is no doubt that it will pave the way for other vaccines of this type.
This technology is being tested for many uses beyond vaccines – for treatments for oncological diseases, for example.
Their effectiveness is that the substance remains in the body for a very short time – enters, does its action, and then breaks down.
This technology is not new, but it has received a serious boost due to the very great need for a rapid vaccine.
Now, for example, we know that the three-week interval between doses is too small, and some vaccine experts claim that it is possible that after the third dose we will no longer need the vaccine in the near term, so it is not clear whether we are going to a situation of vaccination every six months or whether the third dose will provide a larger interval."
